@dhermes, I think we talked about this back and forth a little bit, but as you can see from the system tests, the surface is much different between `sync_recognize()`'s results and `async_recognize()`'s results.

There will be some updates for the gRPC version of `sync_recognize()` that will follow this as well.

This would be helpful to have for unmounting React-based renderers when outputs are cleared and prevent duplicate instances of the components.

Usage within a renderer:

```js
this.element.on('cleared', () => {
   ReactDOM.unmountComponentAtNode(toinsert[0]);
});
```

@fmarier, I've updated the Debian packaging over the last few days, based off of the git history as of dd4b8e87cbddff68273104825aabef0b34f9b284.

I broke it out into multiple binary packages, verified all the tests run clean, and tested the installation.  Everything seems to work.  Lintian is complaining mostly about expected things - UNRELEASED, as well as a couple of manpage errors - but nothing that's too unexpected.  I spent a couple of days trying to use the standard toolset to get this to build properly - pybuild, etc., but ended up having to go with a more manual process.  I squashed a lot of my attempts down in this branch, but an alternate strategy is still extant on my branch at hlieberman/debian-failed-attempt.

Please let me know if this looks good to you, and upstream can merge after your thumbs up.
